Demonstration of NetCDF I/O module. Requires scipy.
The simulation outputs two trajectories, one in xyz format and the other
in Amber-compatible NetCDF format.
One can convert both of the output trajectories to xyz format using
i-pi-mux-positions.

For example,
i-pi input.xml
i-pi-mux-positions --filename-out simulation.fromxyz.xyz simulation.xc1.xyz
i-pi-mux-positions --filename-out simulation.fromnc.xyz simulation.xc2.nc

The simulation.fromxyz.xyz and simulation.fromnc.xyz files will have the
same coordinates, but different atom names. Specifically, the
Amber-compatible NetCDF format only stores coordinates, not the names,
so "XX" is instead output.

